# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1971-swiss-referendums
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1798-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum was held in the Helvetic Republic over several months in 1798.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1798-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] Modelled after the French Constitution of the Year III of 1795, the new constitution was approved by voters.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1798-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] In some places voting took places in public assemblies, whilst in others the local councils took the decision.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1802-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum was held in the Helvetic Republic on 25 May 1802.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1802-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] Unlike the constitution approved in 1798, the new constitution, known as the Malmaison constitution, did not provide for any referendums.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1802-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] Non-voters were assumed to have voted in favour of the new constitution, a measure put in place to prevent its rejection.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1802-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] As a result, 72.17% of voters were deemed to be in favour.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum was held in Switzerland in July and August 1848, the first referendum on record in the Swiss Confederation.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-constitutional-referendum] The new constitution was approved by 72.8% of voters and a majority of cantons.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-constitutional-referendum] In order to pass, any amendments to the constitution needed a double majority; a majority of the popular vote and majority of the cantons.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-constitutional-referendum] The decision of each canton was based on the vote in that canton.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-constitutional-referendum] Full cantons counted as one vote, whilst half cantons counted as half.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-federal-election] Federal elections were held in Switzerland between 1 and 27 October 1848.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-federal-election] The Radical Left emerged as the largest group, winning 79 of the 111 seats in the National Council.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-federal-election] The 111 members of the National Council were elected from 52 single- and multi-member constituencies.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-federal-election] In six cantons (Appenzell Innerrhoden, Appenzell Ausserrhoden, Glarus, Nidwalden, Obwalden and Uri), National Council members were elected by the Landsgemeinde.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] Federal elections were held in Switzerland on 26 October 1851.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The Radical Left remained the largest group in the National Council, winning 78 of the 120 seats.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The elections were held under the Federal law concerning the elections to the National Council, which had been passed on 21 December 1850.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The 120 members of the National Council were elected in 49 single- and multi-member constituencies; there was one seat for every 20,000 citizens, with seats allocated to cantons in proportion to their population.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The 1850 law reduced the number of constituencies from 52, but increased the number of seats from 111; Aargau, Glarus, Lucerne, Neuchâtel, Vaud and Zürich gained one seat each, whilst Bern gained three seats.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The law also set the election date as the last Sunday in October and introduced a three-year term.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The elections were held using a three-round system; candidates had to receive a majority in the first or second round to be elected; if it went to a third round, only a plurality was required.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] Voters could cast as many votes as there were seats in their constituency.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1854-swiss-federal-election] Federal elections were held in Switzerland on 29 October 1854.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1854-swiss-federal-election] The Radical Left remained the largest group in the National Council, winning 80 of the 120 seats.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1857-swiss-federal-election] Federal elections were held in Switzerland on 28 October 1857.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1857-swiss-federal-election] Compulsory voting was introduced in the Canton of Schaffhausen for the elections, with the canton seeing the highest turnout at 86.4% compared to the 46.5% figure nationally.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1971-swiss-referendums] Three referendums were held in Switzerland in 1971.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1971-swiss-referendums] The first was held on 7 February on introducing women's suffrage at the federal level, and was approved by 66% of voters.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1971-swiss-referendums] The second and third were held on 6 June on a constitutional amendment to introduce the human right to a non-hazardous environment and a federal resolution on federal finances.
[src:1971-swiss-referendums/1971-swiss-referendums] In the first referendum in which women were allowed to vote, both were approved by voters.
